ok to offer a long-term perspective on vaccination across different vaccine types. This history provides context for students and researchers interested in present-day controversies surrounding public health immunisation programmes. Historians of the post-war British welfare state will find valuable insight into changing public attitudes towards institutions of government and vice versa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aBritain.  aBritish public.  aHistoriography.  aPolicy.  aPublic health.  aVaccination.  aWelfare state.1 aMillward, Gareth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2019 eBook-Packagez978311128249740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526126764zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526126764zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526126764/original  a978-3-11-128249-7 Manchester University Press 2019 eBook-Packageb2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA